13 (5) Initial application for an out-of-state applicant.
14 (6) All other applications.
15 (7) Criminal history check.
16 An applicant must pay any nonrefundable or nontransferable service fees at the time an
17 application is submitted."
18 SECTION 2.(d) Article 17E of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is amended by
19 adding a new section to read:
20 "§ 115C-270.12. Licensure criminal history checks.
21 (a) The State Board of Education shall require an applicant that is applying for a license
22 under this Article that has never previously applied for any license under this Article in this State
23 to be checked for a criminal history before the applicant is issued a license.
24 (b) An applicant for licensure may be employed on a temporary basis while the State
25 Board is checking the applicant's criminal history and making a decision based on the results of
26 the check.
27 (c) An applicant is responsible for paying any fees associated with conducting the
28 criminal history check authorized under this section, but a governing body of a public school unit
29 may pay for the criminal history check on behalf of the applicant.
30 (d) The State Bureau of Investigation shall provide to the State Board of Education the
31 criminal history from the State and National Repositories of Criminal Histories of any applicant
32 for licensure. The State Board shall require the applicant to (i) be fingerprinted and to provide
33 any additional information required by the State Bureau of Investigation to a person designated
34 by the State Board and (ii) sign a form consenting to the check of the criminal record and to the
35 use of fingerprints and other identifying information required by the repositories. The State Board
36 shall not issue a license to an applicant who refuses to consent to a criminal history check.
37 (e) The State Board of Education shall review the criminal history it receives on an
38 applicant. The State Board shall determine whether the results of the review indicate that the
39 applicant (i) poses a threat to the physical safety of students or personnel, (ii) has demonstrated
40 that he or she does not have the integrity or honesty to fulfill his or her duties as a professional
41 educator, or (iii) otherwise fails to meet the standards and criteria adopted by the State Board
42 governing the ethics and moral character required for professional educators and shall use the
43 information when making licensure decisions. If the State Board denies an applicant based on its
44 review of the criminal history it receives, the State Board shall make written findings with regard
45 to how it used the information when making licensure decisions.
46 (f) During the period of licensure, the State Board of Education may, upon request,
47 provide the criminal history it receives on an applicant to the governing body of a public school
48 unit considering employment of that individual.
49 (g) All of the information received by the State Board of Education through the checking
50 of the criminal history in accordance with this section is privileged information and is not a public
51 record but is for the exclusive and confidential use of the State Board and the governing board
DRH40433-NH-155 Page 3

