1 of a public school unit considering employment of an individual granted licensure. The State
2 Board may destroy the information used for the purposes authorized by this section after the
3 licensure of the individual has ended or has been renewed. The governing body of a public school
4 unit may destroy the information after it is used for the purposes authorized by this section after
5 one calendar year.
6 (h) There shall be no liability for negligence on the part of the State Board of Education,
7 or its employees, arising from any act taken or omission by any of them in carrying out the
8 provisions of this section. The immunity established by this subsection shall not extend to gross
9 negligence, wanton conduct, or intentional wrongdoing that would otherwise be actionable. The
10 immunity established by this subsection shall be deemed to have been waived to the extent of
11 indemnification by insurance, indemnification under Articles 31A and 31B of Chapter 143 of the
12 General Statutes, and to the extent sovereign immunity is waived under the Tort Claims Act, as
13 set forth in Article 31 of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes.
14 (i) Any applicant for licensure who willfully furnishes, supplies, or otherwise gives false
15 information on a licensure application that is the basis for a criminal history record check under
16 this section shall be guilty of a Class A1 misdemeanor."
17 SECTION 2.(e) The State Board of Education is encouraged to work toward
18 programming the licensure system to align with the Multistate Educator Lookup System
19 established by the National Association of State Directors of Teacher Education and Certification
20 to enable electronic validation of out-of-state credentials and related information.
21 SECTION 2.(f) This section applies to applications for licensure that are received
22 on or after October 1, 2025.
