24 PART III. CRIMINAL HISTORY CHECKS FOR PUBLIC SCHOOL UNIT
25 PERSONNEL
26 SECTION 3.(a) There is established in Article 7B of Chapter 115C of the General
27 Statutes a new Part to read "Part 7. Public School Unit Personnel."
28 SECTION 3.(b) G.S. 115C-332 is recodified into Part 7 of Article 7B of Chapter
29 115C of the General Statutes, as established by this act, as G.S. 115C-77 and reads as rewritten:
30 "§ 115C-77. School personnel criminal history checks.
31 (a) As used The following definitions apply in this section:
32 (1) "Criminal history" means a Criminal history. – A county, state, or federal
33 criminal history of conviction of a crime, whether a misdemeanor or a felony,
34 that indicates the employee (i) poses a threat to the physical safety of students
35 or personnel, or (ii) has demonstrated that he or she does not have the integrity
36 or honesty to fulfill his or her duties as public school personnel. Such crimes
37 include the following North Carolina crimes contained in any of the following
38 Articles of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes: Article 5A, Endangering
39 Executive and Legislative Executive, Legislative, and Court Officers; Article
40 6, Homicide; Article 7B, Rape and Kindred Other Sex Offenses; Article 8,
41 Assaults; Article 10, Kidnapping and Abduction; Article 13, Malicious Injury
42 or Damage by Use of Explosive or Incendiary Device or Material; Article 14,
43 Burglary and Other Housebreakings; Article 15, Arson and Other Burnings;
44 Article 16, Larceny; Article 17, Robbery; Article 18, Embezzlement; Article
45 19, False Pretense and Cheats; Article 19A, Obtaining Property or Services
46 by False or Fraudulent Use of Credit Device or Other Means; Article 20,
47 Frauds; Article 21, Forgery; Article 26, Offenses Against Public Morality and
48 Decency; Article 26A, Adult Establishments; Article 27, Prostitution; Article
49 28, Perjury; Article 29, Bribery; Article 31, Misconduct in Public Office;
50 Article 35, Offenses Against the Public Peace; Article 36A, Riots, Civil
51 Disorders, and Emergencies; Article 39, Protection of Minors; and Article 60,
