1 Computer-Related Crime. Such crimes also include possession or sale of
2 drugs in violation of the North Carolina Controlled Substances Act, Article 5
3 of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes, and alcohol-related offenses such as
4 sale to underage persons in violation of G.S. 18B-302 or driving while
5 impaired in violation of G.S. 20-138.1 through G.S. 20-138.5. In addition to
6 the North Carolina crimes listed in this subparagraph, such crimes also include
7 similar crimes under federal law or under the laws of other states.
8 (2) Consumer reporting agency. – An entity which, for monetary fees, dues, or on
9 a cooperative nonprofit basis, regularly engages in whole or in part in the
10 practice of assembling or evaluating consumer credit information or other
11 information on consumers, including criminal history checks, for the purpose
12 of furnishing consumer reports to third parties, and which uses any means or
13 facility of interstate commerce for the purpose of preparing or furnishing
14 consumer reports, and which is regulated as provided in 15 U.S.C. § 1681, et
15 seq. A criminal history check by a consumer reporting agency provided for
16 purposes of this section must include all of the following:
17 a. A search of the state criminal registry or repository in which the
18 applicant resides.
19 b. A multistate/multijurisdiction database search which includes a
20 follow-up search at the originating source for any information returned
21 by the database search and which confirms final disposition
22 information of the same.
23 c. A search of records obtained from county, state, and federal criminal
24 repositories where the individual resides and has previously resided.
25 d. A search of the National Sex Offender Registry established as
26 provided in 42 U.S.C. § 16919.
27 (3) Governing body. – The governing body of a public school unit.
28 (2)(4) "School personnel" means any:School personnel. – Any of the following:
29 a. Employee of a local board of education public school unit whether
30 full-time or part-time, orpart-time.
31 b. Independent contractor or employee of an independent contractor of a
32 local board of education, public school unit, if the independent
33 contractor carries out duties customarily performed by school
34 personnel, whether paid with federal, State, local, or other funds, who
35 has significant access to students. School personnel includes substitute
36 teachers, driver training teachers, bus drivers, clerical staff, and
37 custodians.
38 (b) Criminal History Checks Required. – Each local board of education governing body
39 shall adopt a policy on whether and under what circumstances that requires an applicant for a
40 school personnel position shall be required to be checked for a criminal history as provided in
41 subsection (c) of this section before the applicant is offered an unconditional job. Each local
42 board of education governing body shall apply its policy uniformly in requiring applicants for
43 school personnel positions to be checked for a criminal history. A local board of education that
44 requires a criminal history check for an applicant governing body may employ an applicant
45 conditionally while the board governing body is checking the person's criminal history and
46 making a decision based on the results of the check. The criminal history check policy of a
47 governing body shall uniformly require applicants for school personnel employment to be
48 checked for a criminal history either by a consumer reporting agency, the State Bureau of
49 Investigation, or both.
50 A local board of education shall not governing body may require an applicant to pay for the
51 criminal history check authorized under this subsection.
